Answer: The error message you're seeing is because you're trying to use an assignment operator (=) in a context where it's not expected. In Java, the assignment operator is used to assign a value to a variable. However, in your case, you're trying to use it in a context where it's not appropriate.

In your code, you're trying to assign a value to the variable `answer` inside an if-else statement. However, you're not actually doing any assignment here. Instead, you're just calculating the result of the operation and returning it. So, you can remove the assignment operator (=) and just return the result of the operation directly.

Here's how your corrected code should look like:

```java
public double parseEqn(String str) {
   StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(str,"+-/*%",true);
   String first = st.nextToken();
   String op = st.nextToken();
   String second = st.nextToken();
   double ff = Double.parseDouble(first);
   double ss = Double.parseDouble(second);
   double answer;
   if (op.equals("+")){
      answer = ff + ss;
   } else if (op.equals("-")){
      answer = ff - ss;
   } else if (op.equals("/")){
      answer = ff / ss;
   } else {
      answer = ff * ss;
   }
   return answer;
}
```

This code will work as expected and return the double value of the expression passed to it.

Note: I've also removed the parentheses around the else statement. In Java, if-else statements don't need parentheses around the condition.

